{{Infobox philosopher |region = [[Western philosophy]] |era = [[Contemporary philosophy]] |image = |name = Sean Dorrance Kelly |birth_date = |birth_place = |death_date = |death_place = |school_tradition = [[Continental philosophy|Continental]], [[Analytic philosophy|Analytic]] |main_interests = [[phenomenology (philosophy)|phenomenology]], [[existentialism]], [[philosophy of mind]], [[philosophy of perception]], [[philosophy of literature]] |notable_ideas = [[Poiesis|Meta-poiesis]] |influences = [[Martin Heidegger]], [[Maurice Merleau-Ponty]], [[Hubert Dreyfus]] |influenced = }}
'''Sean Dorrance Kelly''' is an American philosopher, currently the Teresa G. and Ferdinand F. Martignetti Professor of Philosophy at [[Harvard University]], where he also serves as Faculty Dean of [[Dunster House]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2017/10/5/faculty-deans-settle/|title=Dunster, Mather House Faculty Deans Settle Into New Positions {{!}} News {{!}} The Harvard Crimson|website=www.thecrimson.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref> A graduate of [[Brown University]], he received his PhD from the [[University of California, Berkeley]]. He is known for his expertise on various aspects of the philosophical, phenomenological, and cognitive neuroscientific nature of [[human experience]].<ref>[https://archive.is/20140206053013/http://arts.nationalpost.com/2011/02/11/book-review-all-things-shining-by-hubert-l-dreyfus-and-sean-dorrance-kelly/ Book Review: All Things Shining, by Hubert L. Dreyfus and Sean Dorrance Kelly]</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/23/books/review/Neiman-t.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 What It All Means]</ref> He is featured in [[Tao Ruspoli]]'s film ''[[Being in the World]]''.
==Books== * ''The Relevance of Phenomenology to the Philosophy of Language and Mind'' (Studies in Philosophy), Sean D. Kelly, Routledge, 2000 * ''All Things Shining: Reading the Western Classics to Find Meaning in a Secular Age'', Hubert Dreyfus and Sean Dorrance Kelly, Free Press, 2011
